sec.p:
Laser irradiation is used in laser chemical machining as a localized and selective heat source that can induce a suitable thermal impact for the activation of a heterogeneous chemical reaction between a liquid environment and a metallic surface, and results in an anodic metal dissolution under the formation of hydrogen and water-soluble metallic salts following the chemical reaction [Bae11]:4.1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ Me + 2H^{ + } \to Me^{2 + } + H_{2} \uparrow $$\end{document}

The thermal model developed is described in detail in [Mes17a]. It is based on the solution of the dimensionless heat equation Ψ(X, Y, 0, τ) using a Green-function approach and provides the following description of surface temperature rise T(x, y, 0, t):4.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \begin{aligned} T = \frac{{P_{L} \cdot \alpha_{abs} \cdot \tau_{E} }}{4\pi \cdot \kappa \cdot l} & \cdot \int\limits_{0}^{\tau } {\frac{1}{1 + 4\phi } \cdot \frac{a}{{(a - 1)\sqrt {\pi \alpha^{2} \phi } + \sqrt {\pi \alpha^{2} \phi + a^{2} } }} \cdot e^{{ - \left[ {\frac{{(X - \mu \phi )^{2} + Y^{2} }}{1 + 4\phi }} \right]}} d\phi } \\ - \frac{{P_{L} \cdot \alpha_{abs} \cdot \tau_{E} }}{4\pi \cdot \kappa \cdot l} & \cdot \theta \int\limits_{0}^{\tau } {\frac{1}{1 + 4\phi } \cdot e^{{ - \left[ {\frac{{(X - \mu \phi )^{2} + Y^{2} }}{1 + 4\phi }} \right]}} } \\ & \cdot \int\limits_{0}^{\infty } {\frac{a}{{(a - 1)\sqrt {\pi \left( {\frac{{Z^{\prime}}}{4\phi } +\Theta ^{2} \phi +\Theta Z^{\prime}} \right)} + \sqrt {\pi \left( {\frac{{Z^{\prime}}}{4\phi } +\Theta ^{2} \phi +\Theta Z^{\prime}} \right) + a^{2} } }}} \\ & \cdot e^{{ - \frac{{Z^{{{\prime }\,2}} }}{4\phi }}} \cdot e^{{ - \alpha Z^{\prime}}} dZ^{\prime}\,d\phi \\ \end{aligned} $$\end{document}

On the example of machining titanium (3.7024) and stainless steel (AISI304) in a 5 molar phosphoric acid environment, the surface temperatures were calculated depending on laser power PL and feed velocity vfeed. The main process parameters and the properties of the materials and electrolyte used are listed in Table 4.2.Table 4.2
