The surface model is also applied to determine the geometry of the contact zone between tool and workpiece to estimate the load F. The interaction is modeled by a one mass oscillator, equation4.17\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ m\ddot{\delta } + d\dot{\delta } + k\delta = F $$\end{document}with tool deflection \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \delta $$\end{document} and cutting force F. The physical constants m, d, k depend on the process dynamics and are treated as scalar model constants, identified with help of parameter identification methods.

The obtained mathematical model is used to find process parameters that will reduce the deviation of the surface. For parameter identification in calibration and to reduce deviation in the manufacturing process, mathematical optimization and inverse problem methods are used. The forward model is noted with A and takes the parameter \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ u \in U $$\end{document} as input, which is mapped onto the measurement \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ v \in V $$\end{document} by the model A. In parameter identification, F and v are known and a suitable u has to be found. This can be done by minimizing4.18\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \left\| {A(u) - v} \right\|, $$\end{document}which in the ideal case has a minimum of 0. If only the right-hand side of the equation4.19\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ A(u) = v $$\end{document}is of interest, then the resulting problem is a optimization problem. If the parameter u itself is of interest, for example for indirect measurements or to find true model parameters, then the problem at hand is an inverse problem [Rie03, Lou01]. The boundaries between these two cases are not strict and some methods are used for both aspects of parameter identification. In the subproject C2 of the SFB 747 inverse methods were used to identify model parameters from experiments through indirect measurements. This still holds true for the model parameter selection in this subproject T4 because it is based on the same model. In addition, the field of inverse problems addresses the issue of noised data and ill-posed problems. Noised data means that instead of ideal data v or measurements, a small perturbed version \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ v^{\delta } $$\end{document} is known. An ill-posed problem refers to characteristics of the model A, which will result in large deviations of the reconstructed u if \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ v^{\delta } $$\end{document} has small perturbations. In combination, this leads to small error in measurements to large error in the parameter identification. To solve this issue, several different types of regularizations are used to handle the ill-posed nature of the model. In Fig. 4.63, the forward model and inverse problem are visualized.Fig. 4.63
Visualization of inverse problems

The micro and macro models used in this work are both ill-posed and need regularization for parameter identification. Tikhonov’s method with classic and sparsity penalty terms are used to handle the ill-posed nature of the model at hand. For Tikhonov Regularization a functional4.20\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ J_{\alpha ,\delta }^{p,q} (u) = \frac{1}{p}\left\| {A(u) - v^{\delta } } \right\|_{p}^{p} + \alpha \frac{1}{q}\Re_{q} (u) $$\end{document}is minimized. This functional consists of two terms: a discrepancy term that minimizes the distance between simulated and given data and a penalty term on the parameter u that stabilizes the parameter identification. A classical choice for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \Re_{q} $$\end{document} is \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \Re_{q} (u) = \left\| u \right\|_{q}^{q} $$\end{document} with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ q = 2 $$\end{document} or sparsity regularization a certain structure of few active basis elements for the parameter in a defined basis of the space U is assumed. While a \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ l_{0} $$\end{document}-norm on the basis coefficient would best represent this idea, it is not very practical for numerical computation. Instead, a \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ l_{1} $$\end{document}-norm on the basis coefficients of is used as penalty term (for more information on sparsity see [Jin12]).

Since the model A is non-linear, iterative methods are used to find the desired minimizer. Depending on the parameter type different methods are used. For small dimension vector parameters, a sequential quadratic programming (SQP) and gradient descent solver are used [Boy14]. To compensate the deviation of surface, the cutting tool path needs to be adjusted. This leads to a high dimensional parameter and, therefore, too many cost intensive iterations for a SQP or gradient descent method. To reduce the dimension, a greedy approach is used by dividing the tool path into i intervals of equal length. Therefore, the parameter u is a composition of parameters \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ u_{k} $$\end{document} on the defined intervals. Instead to finding u at once each \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ u_{k} $$\end{document} is found in succession of the prior \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ U_{k - 1} $$\end{document}. This leads to multiple minimization problems which are based on solutions found on the first intervals. This way the dimension of each minimization problem is reduced; however, the resulting composition of all \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ u_{k} $$\end{document} might not be a local minimum on the whole tool path.

Processing the row data is essential for comparison and application in optimization. Because simulation and measurement need to be aligned, a shift on the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
